<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by London First (FD04)</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold">London First</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold"> (FD04)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.72pt; padding-left:2.58pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">London First is a business member</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">ship</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> organisation representing almost 200 of the largest companies in London. Our mission is to make London the best place in the world in which to do business.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> The views expressed below relate to London: however we believe that similar arrangements would simi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">larly benefit other English city-regions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Fiscal devolution</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.72pt; padding-left:2.58pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">The amount of UK local government expenditure which is funded by locally raised and retained taxes is very compared to other countries; the Greater London Authority (GLA) has calculated that 7 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">per cent of all the tax paid by London’s residents and businesses is retained by the Mayor of London and the Boroughs while the equivalent figure for New York is 50 per cent. While there have been moves towards devolution from central government to the nat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">ions, UK cities remain almost entirely reliant on central government funding decisions. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.72pt; padding-left:2.58pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">We believe that this is inefficient and that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">London Government (by which we mean the boroughs and the Greater London Authority (GLA)) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">retain a greater portion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">of the taxes raised in London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> at levels broadly consistent with current spending. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">would have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">two advantages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.95pt; padding-left:5.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">first, such retention would create</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; text-decoration:underline">stability and certainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> of funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">to enable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">Government to plan over the long-term, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">s opposed to relying on innately uncertain central government spending reviews</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> and departmental grants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.95pt; padding-left:5.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">second, if London Government relied on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">taxes it captured </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">to fund its activities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">it would have an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; text-decoration:underline">incentive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> to support the economic growth that would lead to an increase in the yield from those taxes. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.72pt; padding-left:2.58pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">Linking London Government’s revenues to the growth in its economy and creating a more stable planning framework is particularly important now given the city’s f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">orecast </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">population growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">. The GLA’s central demographic forecast, using the 2011 census data, is that London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">grow by almost a million people over this decade, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">surpass its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">historic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">1939 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">population </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">peak </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">middle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">decade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> and rea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">ch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">9 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">million by 2020</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">. To put this in context, London will grow by the population </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">Birmingham over this decade. A further million of growth is forecast for the next decade. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">require sustained investment in public infrastructure, not least in transpor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">t but also housing and a range of social infrastructure.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.72pt; padding-left:2.58pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">We support the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">recommendation in the recent report of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">Mayor’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><a href="http://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/Raising%20the%20capital.pdf"><span style="color:#1155cc; font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; text-decoration:underline">London Finance Commission</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> (LFC) that a suit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> of property taxes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">(council tax, business rates, SDLT, annual tax on enveloped dwellings and capital gains </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">property tax) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">be devolved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> to London Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">his </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">be an important step toward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">broader </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">fiscal devolution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> As the LFC recommended, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">devolution of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">these tax </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">revenue streams to London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">be accompanied by a pound-for-pound reduction in funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> by central government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">uture growth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">revenue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> streams</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> would then </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">be retained in London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> (with the national Exchequer continuing to ret</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">ain the benefit from growth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">other tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">s)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">.  There would need to be a mechanism for sharing this growth between the boroughs and the GLA: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">while </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">this is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">complex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> and potentially contentious area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">the LFC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">’s work, and the response by both the Mayor and Lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">ndon Councils, demonstrates that it is practicable.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.72pt; padding-left:2.58pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">LFC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> recommend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">ed that the Mayor should have rate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">-setting powers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> over the devolved property taxes and be able to implement smaller taxes.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">We are not persuaded of these arguments. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.72pt; padding-left:2.58pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; text-decoration:underline">Rate setting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">here is a good case that the Mayor could better structure taxes to support London’s growth – for example by rebalancing residential property taxes from high levels of transaction taxes (SDLT) to consumption taxes (the Council Tax)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">. However </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">we would be conc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">erned that business rates could become the target of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">disproportionate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">increases. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">The GLA would need to provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">a robust governance regime which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">commands the support of business before we could support the full devolution of rate setting powers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.72pt; padding-left:2.58pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; text-decoration:underline">New taxes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">(such as a tourist bedroom tax for example) are unlikely to raise substantive revenue but may damage London’s competitiveness relative to other cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">; again, where such taxes would fall on business, we would want clear evidence that business supports the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">tax and its purpose (as, for example, is the case with Business Improvement Districts) before such a tax could be levied.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.72pt; padding-left:2.58pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">While we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">recogni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">there is limited evidence of an economic dividend from devolution</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">our own comparative analysis of other World Cit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">ies found that success and economic growth is strongly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">correlated with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">high levels of city self-government.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">In a recent survey of members we found that seven in ten businesses felt that the Mayor should retain direct control of a greater proportion of tax </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">revenue. Given that the Scottish government already collects SDLT and the Welsh government is currently consulting on this issue, we see no reason why London cannot follow suit. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">FU</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">THER DEVOLVED POWERS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">To ensure London’s local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">communities’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> co-ordinate services and policies effectively the subsidiarity principle should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">continue to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">be applied. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">Public policy should be made at the lowest efficient tier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">We broadly supported </span><a href="http://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/proposals-for-devolution.pdf"><span style="color:#1155cc; font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; text-decoration:underline">The Mayor of London’s Proposals for Devolution</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> (2010) which suggested a suit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> of additional powers to be devolved to London Government. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">While progress has been made on a number of its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">we would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">highlight </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">three </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">areas where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">further work needs to be done:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; text-decoration:underline">Transport</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">London has an effective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">agency for transport services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">, Transport for London (TfL)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> which is controlled by the Mayor. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">We would like to see the mayor be given further powers, including: </span></li></ol><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.5pt; padding-left:5.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">a greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">role in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> the awarding and monitoring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">the rail franchises for suburban rail lines largely contained within the boundaries of greater London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.5pt; padding-left:5.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">the power to appoint the Board of the Port of London Authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt"> (with provisions to ensure that authorities outside of L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">ondon have appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">representation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">); and </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.5pt; padding-left:5.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">greater flexibility over traffic control on (TfL) roads so that he can develop more effective solutions to get traffic in London flowing more smoothly.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; text-decoration:underline">Skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; text-decoration:underline">, employment and housing</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">Discussions are underway between London Councils and the GLA over devolving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">skills, employment and housing powers as part of the Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">City </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">Growth Deal agenda</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">; and this work is being led by the London Enterprise Panel (LEP)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">While the LEP has not ye</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">t finalised its proposals, we support the principle of further devolution in these areas.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; text-decoration:underline">Utility regulators accountability</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">Finally, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">we believe that the utility regulators should have a similar level of accountability to London government as they have to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">devolved assemblies elsewhere in the UK. London has a set of distinctive needs around utility infrastructure which business does not feel is adequately reflected in the price setting and investment planning processes; greater scrutiny at a London level wou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">ld help ensure these issues are properly considered without compromising the regulators’ independence.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold">John Dickie</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold">Director of Strategy &amp; Policy</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold">London First</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-style:italic">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A. Pike, A. Rodríguez-Pose, J. Tomaney, G. Torrisi and V. Tselios (2010), In Search of the ‘Economic Dividend’ of Devolution: Spatial Disparities, Spatial Economic Policy and Decentralization in the UK , SERC Discussion P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">aper No.62, October 2010</span></p></body></html>